I've been giving some thought to the effects of "Ten Days..."
and here is my analysis, fwiw.

Rule 693

      The prescribed Voting Period for a Proposal is seven days,
      beginning at the time the Proposal is distributed to all
      Players.

It seems to me that a voting period is either an attribute of proposals or a separate nomic entity associated with proposals.  In either case, the duration of a VP is clearly (IMO) a rule defined attribute as well.  I do not think that the end of a VP is itself an event.  Rather, it is a time at which the Rules specify certain events are to occur (e.g. the change in legal status for certain types of messages, the imposition of an obligation to report on the Assessor).

As you can see, I must be a proponent of the Attribute Model.  I don't think anyone would dispute the idea that Rule Changes can and do alter the attributes of entities within the game.  So what do I think are the implications here?

1.  The adoption of "Ten Days..." changed the voting period duration attribute of current and future proposals (or the duration attribute of current and future VPs) to be seven days.

2.  R108 prevents this attribute change from changing the legal significance of any events that occurred prior to the proposal's adoption (i.e. votes cast after seven days but before its adoption would still have been legal votes).

--Crito
