>> > retroactively changed, then I think that's a serious (indeed, fatal)
>> > problem with Andre's position, even if there weren't actually any votes
>> > cast during that period.
>> 
>> That is exactly what my point of view does NOT do. For each Vote, my
>> position makes its legality AT THE MOMENT IT WAS CAST to be the deciding
>> factor. It's exactly that the legality of votes in this period are NOT
>> changed which discerns my (D+7.1) view from the D+7 view.
>> 
>Perhaps one should be considering the problem from other angles. What
>if the voting period had been changed from seven days to ten days?
>Since the problem of retroactivity wouldn't come in, I don't think
>there would have be much objection to extending the VP of Proposals
>already in the queue. Under the attribute model, that would not be
>a correct application of the Rules.

We don't have to wonder 'what if'; once upon a time, on April 28, 1995
to be exact, the Voting Period *was* changed from 7 days to 10, when
P1564 was adopted. And it's interesting to note that the VPs of the
Proposals distributed along with P1564 (1563-1580) were not extended.
Although that's not quite the same case, of course: you were talking
about Proposals already in the Queue (which of course we didn't have in
1995) which have not been distributed. Furthermore, we might want to
distinguish between the treatment of P1563-1564, and the treatment of
P1565-1580, with the thought that Proposals take effect in numerical
order.

Still, your claim about the attribute model is incorrect. What the
attribute model says is that the length of the VP of a Proposal is
established when it is distributed. If we now were to amend R693 so that
it once again specified a VP of 10 days, of course any Proposals which
were distributed after the amendment was adopted would have VPs of 10
days. Their merely having been in the Queue prior to the adoption of the
amendment is irrelevant.

