Steve wrote:

>I think I could live with this solution. Chuck and Scott have objected
>that this would mean that the Proposals had VPs of neither 7 nor 10
                                                                ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
>days, but I think there may be game custom to support this.

But this would be a false and misleading conclusion because it conflates
the concept of what *is* a Proposal's VP with what *was* a Proposal's VP.
For example, what *is* the VP of Proposal 3500?  Well, according to the
current Rule set, it's seven days from the time of the proposal's distribution
(which is just an historical period of time that has no legal consequences).
But, of course, before the passage of "Ten Days...' the VP of Proposal 3500
*was* ten days from the time of its distribution.

 So you see, at no time did the proposals in question ever have a VP that was
other than seven or ten days in duration.  It's just that, because the duration of
the VP changed from one day to the next, the period of time in which votes
could legally be cast was of an intermediate duration.  Note that "Voting Period",
because of the way it is defined, is *not* required to be logically equivalent to
"the period of time in which votes may legally be cast".  Of course, the two
*will* be logically equivalent as long as the definition of a particular VP does
not change during its course.

--Crito

