David Albertz wrote:
>
>Steve wrote:
>
>>I think I could live with this solution. Chuck and Scott have objected
>>that this would mean that the Proposals had VPs of neither 7 nor 10
>>days, but I think there may be game custom to support this.
>
>But this would be a false and misleading conclusion because it
>conflates the concept of what *is* a Proposal's VP with what *was* a
>Proposal's VP. For example, what *is* the VP of Proposal 3500?  Well,
>according to the current Rule set, it's seven days from the time of the
>proposal's distribution (which is just an historical period of time
>that has no legal consequences). But, of course, before the passage of
>"Ten Days...' the VP of Proposal 3500 *was* ten days from the time of
>its distribution.
>
>So you see, at no time did the proposals in question ever have a VP
>that was other than seven or ten days in duration.  It's just that,
>because the duration of the VP changed from one day to the next, the
>period of time in which votes could legally be cast was of an
>intermediate duration.  Note that "Voting Period", because of the way
>it is defined, is *not* required to be logically equivalent to "the
>period of time in which votes may legally be cast".  Of course, the two
>*will* be logically equivalent as long as the definition of a
>particular VP does not change during its course.

I think you have to admit that it's pretty wacky to claim that the
effect of the passage of P3809 is to make it the case that every single
Proposal in the history of the game should now be said to have (present
tense) a Voting Period of 7 days. When I ask the question "how long was
the Voting Period of P3552?" (which I was asking myself just this
morning), I don't expect to get the answer back: "do you mean 'how long
was it before the passage of P3809?' or 'how long was it after the
passage of P3809?'" I just want you tell me how much time there was
between the actual historical beginning and end of the VP of the
Proposal.

On the other hand, I can see why you are forced into saying such wacky
things: it's a direct result of viewing R693 merely as attaching a
designation to an historical period of time, rather than the more
sensible view (as I see things), that it acts to specify when certain
events - the beginning and end of the VP - occur.

